tip.text: Pod beds look very futuristic - there's a couple of different variants they have so you might get old or new design pods. Relaxation room with Netflix / games consoles. Their breakfast is a ripoff.
Extremely simple menu, often just a choice of vegetarian or meat based soup in a bread bowl. Proudly serving no wifi.
Pace yourself with the food, and go easy on the bread and mashed potatoes to save space. On the flip side, I'm not a fan of fish with bones and you need to watch out for that even when "de-boned".
Go-to place during my time in Cape Town for breakfast / lunch for its refreshing and healthy meals! Portion sizes for the frozen yoghurt is good for sharing. Filtered water available near a corner.

tip.text: Absolutely adore the old school telephones in the rooms! And if you're looking for quieter rooms, you can request them - balcony-facing ones are quite noisy as they are right above Princes Street.
Rebranded recently from the Royal Hotel to an Indigo, it's better location than the other one at York Place. Friendly staff and genuinely good wifi. Faced issues with hot water taps malfunctioning.
‪Clever, much-appreciated touch: USB + UK + EU charging sockets at (most) seats. That's why I love flying from this airport whenever I can!‬

tip.text: Service is attentive, music isn't too loud. Prefer inside seating to outside. Excellent mescal cocktails, my recommendation would be to get the smoky one.
Try the fruit beers sampler. Wouldn't drink an entire pint / vaso perhaps but the tastes are unique enough to give a try in small measure sizes.
Cannot stop raving enough about this cafe. The decor is incredibly unique and I could spend hours admiring it. Milkshakes and coffees especially good. Chilled out music playlist.

Hulk Smash is a great way to call it a night (or get one started)
Eau de Cocktail comes in an actual Eau de parfum bottle.
By far the standout feature of this hotel is the cool artwork throughout, especially the collection of wall paintings that give the illusion of 3D!

tip.text: This place is highly recommended. Within the "Tooth Temple" complex. Comprehensive tour of the different forms of Buddhism and landmarks around the world, not just Sri Lanka. Worth the entrance fee.
Fascinating Buddhist temple of the Theravada school. Do walk around the complex, not just the main temple.

tip.text: Pinnawala is a government-run place where you're not allowed to touch the animals and it's all run by trained handlers, as opposed to Millennium. Entry is 2500 LKR for foreigners, 700 LKR for SAARC.
Great view of the ocean and the food is surprisingly good. Go grab breakfast there after a swim, the eggs Benedict is done nicely. Cocktails are quite strong (love it that way!)
Absolutely charming decor: there's a distinct Indian film theme, from 70-80s Bollywood to regional cinema posters from South and East India as well. Get the bottled water which goes towards charity.
Avoid this place during the evening if you're out of town. Mostly it's safe but there are hobos and drunks around who can sometimes be aggressive.
Try the ginger latte - it's not just "spiced" like some coffee shops do it, but actually has the flavour seeped in.
Shout (okay, maybe not) "kaedama" and they'll bring over another round of ramen; make sure you have enough of the soup left to add the ramen to!
